Try this:

    //SharedPreferences key names:
    final String NAME = &quot;name&quot;;
    final String AVATAR = &quot;avatar&quot;;
    final String USER_ID = &quot;user_id&quot;;

You see, what gets passed to `putString()/getString()` is the _contents_ of the variable. The name for the variable itself (e.g., `AVATAR`) is inconsequential.

When you passed the empty string (&quot;&quot;) for both `NAME` and `AVATAR`, the `SharedPreferences` thought you were referencing the entry called &quot;&quot;. So you thought you had two discrete entries, but really you only had one, with the same name, and they were clobbering each other.

The values you choose as the key names (e.g., &quot;name&quot;, &quot;avatar&quot;, &quot;user_id&quot;) are arbitrary, but they are written to the `SharedPreferences` file, and will be visible to anyone reading that file in a text editor. For that reason, it helps to choose descriptive values.

